profiles essential for a potential delivery system. Additionally, the cytotoxicity analysis, migration assay, and combination index analysis emphasized the synergistic effect among copper and lactoferrin, eventually resulting in higher anti-cancer activity against malignant melanoma cells (A375) and that too at very low concentrations, indicating enhanced efficacy. Lactoferrin binds to lactoferrin binding receptors and enters the cytosol of cells. There it downregulates the Bcl-2, leading to ROS generation which further causes DNA damage, oxidative stress and mitochondrial dysfunction which eventually leads to apoptosis through activating cytochrome c and caspases. On the other hand copper ions causes ROS generation and follow the same pathway as lactoferrin and causes apoptosis. Along with this, copper causes cuproptosis via decreasing iron-sulphur cluster proteins and leads to cellular dysfunction and eventually cell death. The mechanism of action of Cu-LFNPs is shown in Fig. 6  Fig. 6 The figure illustrates mechanistic insights into the anti-cancer effect of synthesized Cu-LFNPs. The lactoferrin interacts with cancerous cells through the receptors present on the cell membranes, and lactoferrin, along with copper ions, gets released into the cytosol. Both of them cause ROS generation, and lactoferrin leads to apoptosis, and, copper causes cuproptosis eventually resulting in cell death. The green color is indicative of mitochondrial signaling pathway, pink color indicates cytosolic signaling while the blue color indicates the end result of these pathways. Electronic supplementary material Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1 Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements The authors are thankful to Thapar Institute of Engineering and Technology for providing them with all the facilities. Authors are grateful to T